{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_emmental_ver01/data/sn83045293/00517012464/1921012701/0363.xml":{"full_text":"EDITORIAL PAGE\nVol. 10\u2014No. 43.\nTHE MILWAUKEE LEADER\nPublished every evening, except Sunday, by the Milwaukee Social-\nDemocratic Publishing Company, at Chestnut and Sixth Streets.\nVICTOR L. BERGER Editor\nlOn indefinite leave of absence, and not responsible for contents of paper.)\nASSOCIATE EDITORS:\nE. H. THOMAS. JOHN M. M OK IC.\nBUSINESS MANAGER:\nE. W. REHFELD, 528 Chestnut St., Milwaukee, Wis.\nASSISTANT MANAGER:\nMETA BERGER, 528 Chestnut St., Milwaukee, Wis.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES\u2014The Mail Edition of The Milwaukee Deader\nwill be sent to any subscriber in the United States under third class pos ag,\nfer 90 cents per month, $2.50 for three months, $5.00 for six months,\nfor one year.\nThe Home Edition will be delivered in Milwaukee County for 1j s\na week or 65 cents a month. Outside of Milwaukee County 18 cents a\nIf the delivery of your paper is not regular, notify the circulation\npartment. Grand 5060, immediately, and your complaint will be pro p\nattended to.\nOffice Hours: 8A.M.t06 P. M. TeL Grand 5060.\nApplication for entry as second class mail matter is pending.\nIMPRESSIONS OF RABBI WISE\nIn his able address, given under the auspices of the Mil\nwaukee teachers, Rabbi Wise might have closed by saying,\n\"This isn\u2019t all I know!\u201d\nHe was introduced by the convention secretary of the\nAssociation of Commerce. Does this indicate that the Teach\ners\u2019 association and the Association of Commerce have\nsmoked the pipe\u2014beg pardon\u2014munched the chocolates of\npeace?\nAt any rate, there was the convention secretary as big as\nlife on the platform, and doubtless other evidences of regu\nlarity and conservatism that could be sensed by a trained\npublic speaker.\nThe rabbi gave us the impression of a man who was\ncarefully feeling his way and trying to say as much as he\ncould say without getting himself in bad.\nHe did not at any time take a dive to rock bottom in his\ndiscussion of what an American teacher should teach. But\nhe was not wholly superficial\u2014for he did skim along just\nunder the surface now and then.\nFor example, he hinted that our former enemies\u2014Ger\nmany and Austria\u2014although we had helped to vanquish\nthem\u2014had nevertheless triumphed over us in that we had\ntaken on the autocratic methods of coercion which they had\ndropped. Coercion and democracy cannot coexist\u2014he aver\nred.\nHe also said that the child should be taught democracy\n\u2014and that the child should be taught to reason\u2014no matter\nwhere its thinking might lead.\nThat, in fact, was the burden of his message\u2014that both\nteachers and children must think for themselves. That they\nmust not be automatons. That the teachers must not feel\nthat they have signed away their souls.\nOne could wish that he had felt free to tell them why\nthey are not now free to teach the truth\u2014and how they could\nbecome free. Maybe he knows. Maybe he does not. If he\ndoes, he probably thought he was prescribing a big enough\ndose for one time.\nIf the teachers will follow his advice\u2014and think for\nthemselves\u2014it will not take them long to discover that their\nfreedom is shackled because the schools are controlled by\nselfish reactionary pecuniary forces\u2014and that they can\nbreak the shackles by electing a Socialist school board.\nIn jollying the teachers, the rabbi told about a young\ngirl to whom he was called upon to deliver a prize for pro\nficiency in the English language. He asked her if she had\nexpected to win the prize. She replied, \u201cSure, I knew I had\nit cinched!\u201d\nThe teachers can \u201ccinch\u201d their academic freedom, and\nlikewise the democracy of the schools, by turning out en\nmasse and working hand in hand with the real friends of\nthe schools\u2014the Socialists.\nBIG BIZ FLOUTS CONSTITUTION\nu Our constitutional system meets with opposition from\nthose who desire to dominate\u2014individuals whose will the\nsystem checks,\u201d says a writer in The A. C. L. Forum.\nPrecisely.\nBut those individuals who desire to dominate are not\nthe Socialists, as per the impression sought to be given by\nthe self-appointed guardians of the constitution.\nThe masterful men who override the constitution are\nexactly those to whom these alleged constitution upholders\ngive their lavish praise.\nThe constitution has been shot full of holes for the ben\nefit of big business. Parts of it have been twisted out of all\nsemblance to the original meaning, in order to let che plund-\nschemes of big business go through.\nIt has also been split wide open by domineering officials\nwho\u2014also for the benefit of big business\u2014wanted to sup\npress free speech, free press and free assemblage.\nAnd the fawning self-appointed upholders of the con\nstitution explained to their readers that the constitution does\nnot mean what it says.\nSo far, the constitutional system has failed to check\nthe careers of those who desire to dominate. They have\ntramped the constitution in the .mud \u2014with the help of its\nso-called defenders.\nThey will continue to tramp on it until the Socialists\nrescue it from them.\nNO TEARS FOR THE DEAD\nA capitalist\u2019s ideas of personal rectitude are peculiar.\nMr. Schwab cried about that $260,000 voucher affair, in\nwhich he was accused of having used the money for per\nsonal expenses. It wounded him to have his reputation as\nsailed in that manner.\nWe have not heard of him or any other capitalist hav\ning shed tears because their companies made and sold muni\ntions of war with which to kill men in 1915 and 1916, when\nour country w r as supposed to be neutral.\nThe worst of it is that they probably do not feel any\nremorse whatsoever. They probably think it was a stroke\nof good business of which they have a right to be proud.\nYet it helped to take the lives of human beings. And\nit helped to lead our own country into the war\u2014with its toll\nof many thousands of American lives and its fifty billion\ndollars of expense\u2014compared with which $260,000 is a small\nmatter.\nThe Milwaukee Leader\n<Jfllggs CERTNMtt r =r -\u2014\"A\nn \u20147 cold? CePT.n )l*- r\nLoom, jl c avvWkvm,\ni ~f\u2014 Tms I\n1 V-S&TrtER COWSKIH: l co u> o* NO7-\nThe Espionage Act\nIn an article in The Nation, Air.\nWalter Nclles points out that our\nloss of civil Liberty is due to what\nhe calls the \u201ccowed mind.\u201d Every\nbody hates persecutions in general.\nBut few persons will say so in\nany particular case in opposition\nto an imagined contrary opinion.\nThus Mr. Nelles explained how a\ncomparatively small number of\npersons have been able to carry\nout a regime of repression of free\nspeech and press notwithstanding\nthe constitutional provisions guar\nanteeing them.\nCruel as has been the enforce\nment of the espionage act in many\ncases Mr. Nelles says, that with\nout making light of the suffering\nof imprisonment, he believes the\nact has done more harm to people\nout of jail, than to those in jail.\n\nFear of punislunent for political\nheresy lias wrought great injury to\nthe commonwealth by the perver\nsion and suppression of public\nopinion. It is almost impossible\nto find men who will say publicly\nwhat they really think.\nMr. Nelles\u2019 article shows that\nqonvictions under the espionage\nact have in many cases been se\ncured by what he calls \u201can act of\nfaith\u201d on the part of jurymen. The\nlaw forbids \u201cwilful obstruction of\nthe recruiting or enlistment serv\nice of the United States to the in\njury of the service, or of the\nUnited States.\u201d But it is not nec\nessary to prove that any such wil\nful obstruction actually occurred.\nJuries are told that they must\nconvict, if the utterances or writ\ning of the accused had in their\nopinion a tendency to produce the\n\u201cobstruction\u201d which was forbid\nden.\n\nMany persons were convicted\nand sent to prison for utterances\nxery similar to that of President\nWilson, hi a speech at St. Louis, on\nSept. 5, 1919, when he said:\n\u201cWhy my fellow citizens is there\nany man here, or woman, who\ndocs not know\u2019 that the seed of\nwar in the modern world is indus\ntrial and commercial rivalries?\nThis war was a commercial and\nindustrial war.\u201d\n\nNow had President Wilson been\narrested and indicted for saying\nthis, the court and the prosecut\ning attorney would have argued\nthat the war was a war to make\nthe world safe for democracy, and\nto end all future wars, and that\nfor this purpose it was not diffi\ncult to carry on recruiting and\nenlistment. But if the people be\nlieve that plutocratic influences\nwere back of the war they would\nfind President Wilson guilty of\nsaying things which were injurious\nto the United States in prosecut\ning the war.\n4:\nMr. Nelles points out that in this\nway there was re-established a\nform of \u201cconstructive crimes\u201d of\nexactly the same species as the\nold English crimes of seditions\nlibel and constructive treason\nwhich were exactly the things\nwhich the framers of the first\namendment of our constitution in\ntended to make forever impossible\nin this country.\nHi\nCivil liberty was never more im\nportant than today when wage\nworkers and working farmers are\ntaking a greater interest in so\ncial, political and economic re\nforms than ever before. And if\nimproved conditions are to be\nbrought about, in an orderly way,\nby legislative reforms we must do\naway with sedition trials which\nloster hatred and revolution by\ntue intimidation which they pro\nmote. \u2014The Capital Timo\u00bb\nLET'S THINK OF SCHOOL DAYS\nTHURSDAY, JANUARY 27, 1921.\nCopyright, 1921, by McClure Newspaper Syndicate\nPhiladelphia Long\non Economics\nPhiladelphia once stretched\nchains across its streets on Sunday\nto insure that impious men would\nnot desecrate the Sabbath. Phila\ndelphia has not forgotten its early\ngoodness of heart. The industrial\nrelations committee of its chamber\nof commerce advertises in the lo\ncal press just how to meet the in\ndustrial depression and unemploy\nment. It is easy. Consider the\nproblem to be solved.\nThere are many men out of\nwork. \u201cIt is up to the employers\nto .handle this situation and find\nwork for their men wherever and\nhowever possible.\u201d This is stating\nthe question in simple terms. Some\nconcerns have started to renovate\ntheir plants and some are making\nadditions to their plants. So much\nto the good. Now, wbat else is\nnecessary? We quote:\n\u201cIf a worthy man applies to you\nfor u job, it is your duty\u2019 to help\nhim; if you cannot give him one,\ninvite him in\u2014explain to him why\nit is you cannot. Phone to every\nbody you can think of to see what\nyou can do for him. Show this\nman the spirit of sympathy.\u201d\n\nThen what? Show him the\ndoor. What else can be done?\nAnd while you are phoning every\nbody else for him everybody else,\nwill be phoning you about some\none else, and all of you will be\nshowing \u201cthe spirit of sympathy.\u201d\nThen all of these men visiting all\nthe plants where no work can be\nfound will return home profoundly\nimpressed with the \u201csympathy\u201d\nthey got and forget all about the\njob which they did not get. The\nemploying class can also console\nitself with the reflection that doing\nall this \u201cis our right\u2014our exceed\ning great opportunity.\u201d\nIt is all so profound and \u201cup\nlifting\u201d that we are charmed with\nthe novelty of the solution. Hav\ning pursued the subject thus far,\nas it is set forth in the advertise\nment, we come to the last item in\nthis program, which reads as fol\nlows\n\u201cThere is profit to everybody in\nwork; there is loss to everybody\nthrough lack of work. The one\neffective way we can hasten the\nreturn of prosperity is by finding\nwork for the unemployed. Let\nus put the men to work.\u201d\n\nAnd we have just been told what\nis to he expected by the jobless\nmen who apply at idle plants or\nplants that are working short\ntime. They are to he taken in and\nshown the \u201cspirit of sympathy\u201d\nand then shown the door! And\nthis is the output of the leading\nhankers and business men of Phil\nadelphia. Children could do bet\nter. It is an index to the low men\ntal capacities of the banking and\ncapitalist fraternity when con\nfronted with the demoralization of\ntheir own regime.\u2014New York Call\nUnselfishness\nAre you searching for the happi\nness that does not fade away?\nAre you looking for the joy that\nlives and leaves no grievous\nday?\nAre you ]>anting for tlie water\nbrooks of Love, and Life, and\nPeace?\nThen let ail dark desires depart,\nand selfish seeking cease.\nAre you lingering in the paths of\npain, grief-haunted, stricken\nsore\nAre you wand\u2019ring in the ways that\nwound your weary feet the\nmore?\nAre .you sighing Xor the resting\nBY DWIG\nDinner Pail Epic\nBY BELL LLOYD.\nStaff Writer for The Federated Press.\nIn knocking round, one thing I\nseen; it ain\u2019t too easy to keep\nclean. These two-bit flops give one\na bed, but that\u2019s about all can be\nsaid. You get a chanct to wash\nyour face, but that ain\u2019t any high\nlife pace, and when your pants\nbegin to go, they size you up for\nsome hobo. Transparent hose may\nhe quite chic, but trouser seats\nshould be real thick.\nThe other day I hit the path\nthat leads down to the city bath.\nThe city fathers all see red w\u2019hen\n\u201ccommunism\u201d is just said. Sole\nownership is just the thing\u2014that\nis the theory that they sing. If\nthey believe it just one-lialf, why\ncan\u2019t we have a private hath?\nOf course the fellows on the\nhike can\u2019t have just everything\nthey like, but lots of fellows, more\nthan half, that go to that there\ncity hath, are married men in\nshacks near-by, who pay a rent\nmost, awful high, and yet the land\nlord gives no tub to take your\ngood, old week-end scrub.\nIt\u2019s here the city dads for sure\nthink communism is the cure, and\nuse their aldermanic power to put\nmankind beneath one shower, and\npin their futuristic hope on com\nmon ownership of soap. This com\nmunism goes too far, when all\nmust use one kind of bar, and\nwater of the selfsame heat in\nwhich to scrub their erring feet.\nOf course the philanthropic\ndubs don\u2019t ever go there for their\nrubs. They lay their theory on\nthe shelf and have a bathroom for\ntheirself, step from their slippers\nonto tile, instead of walk half\na mile.\nI\u2019m not with these rich, rad\u2019eal\nblokes, hut come out square for\nprivate soaks, to hang my pants on\nmy own peg, when I rub soap on\nmy own leg. I\u2019m just as strong\nfor bathroom locks as Senator\nPhilander Knox!\nIt Is Appalling\nBY PERRY ENGLE.\nThe six bloodiest battles of the\neivil war were those of Gettys\nburg, Spottsylvania, the Wilder\nness, Antietum, Chancellorsville\nand Chickamaugua. The killed,\nwounded and missing in these six\nbattles, on the Union side, aggre\ngated fewer than 105,000 men.\nThe killed and injured on our\nrailroads during the year ending\nJune 30, 1906, were 108,321; with\nan average t>f about 200,000 every\nyear to date.\nOur greedy complex manufac\nturing system under capitalism is\nused only for profits. Human lives\nare regarded only as commodities.\nA laboring man. if sold at auc\ntion to the highest bidder, would\nbring less than a colored chattel\nslave would 70 years ago.\nIt is a shame and a sin that so\nmany of the employers of labor\nare opposed to organized labor, or\nthe right of labor to organize for\nself-protection.\nplace where tears and sorrows\ncease?\nThen sacrifice your selfish heart,\nand. find the Heart of Peace.\n-\u2014James Allen,\nCOIVUM Of\nOLVUMr I\nlin iHiii\u00dfimiriHin\nThe Battle of Barleycorn.\n(Apologies to Southey.)\nProhibition Director Kramer\nsays practical prohibition will\ncome with the next generation\nwho will not be familiar with\nliquor.\u2014News Item.\nIt was without, a hired man,\nOld Kaspar\u2019s work was done,\nAnd he was sitting wishing they\nWeren\u2019t scarce and he had one;\nStill kept down on the farm was\nseen\nHis little grandchild Wilhel\nmine.\nShe saw her brother Peterkin\nRoll something long and round,\nWhich he beside the cellar steps,\nIn playing there, had found;\nHe came to ask what he had\nfound\nThat was so long and smooth\nand round.\nOld Kaspar gave the thing a\nglance\nAnd batted not an eye;\nAnd then the old man shook his\nhead\nAnd heaved a wicked sigh.\n\u2019Tis some beer bottle old, said\nhe,\n\u2019Twas killed in the great vic\ntory.\u201d\n\u201cNow tell us what \u2019twas all\nabout,\u201d\nThe children quickly cry.\n\u201cWhat is this here now beer?\u201d\nthey asked.\n\u201cOh, please do tell us why.\u201d\n(I\u2019or you must know the little\ndears\nWere bom since people ordered\nbeers.\n\u201cIt was the \u2018drys,\u2019 old Kaspar\ncried,\n\u201cWho put the \u2018wets\u2019 to bout;\nAnd how they put tlie thing\nacross\nI never could make out.\nAnd some folks said\u2014it wasn\u2019t\nme\u2014\nThat \u2019twas a famous victory.\n\u201cMy father lived in these parts\nthen,\nHe saw the New Year in;\nAnd yonder in his cellar there\nWas many a well stocked bin.\nYou have one of the \u2018soldiers\ndead,\u2019\nThat gave your great-grandad a\n\u2018bead.\u2019\nOld Kaspar took the bottle up;\nThen knocked he off the neek.\nAnd as he gulped the contents,\nsaid:\n\u201cThe dern thing\u2019s full, by heck!\u201d\nAnd to the children cried in\nglee,\n\u201cThat wash a famush victoree!\u201d\n\u2014F. D. D. in The Kansas City\nStar.\nThe Curl Series.\nThis girl-with-the-curl series\nis spreading. Berton Braley has\nbeen showing how various poets\nmight adapt the jingle of the\nlittle girl who had a little curl\nright in the middle of her fore\nhead. We venture to show how\nS. Jay Kaufman might do it.\nNow comes a contrib who signs\nhimself \u201cClinic,\u201d who offers\nthis:\nAS LONGFELLOW WROTE IT.\nThere was a little girl\nWho had a little curl\nRight in the middle of her\nforehead;\nWhen she was good\nShe was very, very good;\nBut when she was had she\nwas horrid.\nAS H. ADDINGTON BRUCE\nWOULD WRITE IT.\nCase 57\u2014Female, young, nor\nmally small in stature, chief\nphysical peculiarity a diminutive\nexcrescence or overflow of hair,\nconvoluted and extending down\nover median surface of fore\nhead. Dominant characteristic\na temperamental nature, exhib\niting frequent transitions from\ntlie most exemplary character\nand conduct to periods of ex\ntreme obliquity, depression,\nmalevolent moods and a ten\ndency to be vindictive. Prob\nable casual agent, since there\nare no hereditary prodromeda,\nreflex neuroses due to difficult\ndentition or similar peripheral\nirritation. Indications \u2014Surgical\nremoval of curl. \u2014H. I. P. in The\nNew York Globe.\nFor Profit\nThe president of the National\nLeague of Commission Merchants,\nat a convention held in St. Louis\nlast week, made the astonishing\nannouncement that the production\nof fruits and produce had reached\na point where it was greater than\nconsumption. Unfortunately the\nconsumers are not enjoying tlie\nbenefits of this overproduction. In\nSt. Lands, for instance, the com\nmission merchants are not slow in\ndumping carloads of fruits into\nthe river rather than let the public\nhave them at low prices. They are\nin the bus ness for profit, like all\nthe capitalists, and xor this reason\ncannot have any consideration for\nthe welfare of the consumers. Un\nder \u2022Socialism this kind of commis\nsion merchant business would dis\nappear, because production in in\ndustry and agriculture would be\nfor use, not for profit.\u2014St. Louis\nLabor.\nDead Letter Laws\n\u201cIllinois is said to have the best\nchild labor law in the United States,\nyet Chicago factories employ 4.000\nhiore children than ever before.\u201d\n\u2014Cleveland Citizen. The best law\nis not better than the worst if it\nis not enforced, and capitalist pol\niticians are never over-anxious to\nenforce laws tending to interfere\nwith unrestricted, unscrupulous\nprofit-making.\u2014Exchange.\nRECENT BANK CRIME INCREASE\nBY WILLIAM li. JOYCE.\nPresident, the National Surety Co.\nCrimes against banks have very\nseriously increased since the world\nwar. Annual bank embezzlements\nare estimated at $10,000,000: an\nnual bank losses from forgeries\nand altered checks art' believed to\nbe equally severe: annual bank\nholdups and burglaries are total\nlug at least three-quarters of a\nmillion dollars. These figures rep\nresent losses of national and state\nbanks. Recent, heavy embezzle\nment losses of brokerage firms do\ning merely an incidental banking\nbusiness are not included.\nReasons for recent bank crimes\nneed slight analysis. The war\ndrafted the criminal as well as the\npatriot and brought him back to\nus much more reckless regarding\nproperty rights, human l.fe, the\nuse of firealnns, the sudden at\ntacking of crowded and even\nguarded places. The war also\ngreatly increased moral instability,\nthe cost of living, discontent, rest\nlessness, desire for extravagant and\nwasteful pleasures, class jealousy\nand many other highly dangerous\neconomic conditions and psycho\nlogical moods. The present gen\neral nation-wide increase of crime\nis clearly shown by the fact that\nthe National Surety Co. paid two\nand a half times as many em\nbezzlement losses, and half again\nas many burglary and holdup\nlosses in 1920 as in 1919. Amounts\ntaken in individual recent bank\nciimes have also averaged much\ngreater than ever before. More\nthorough \u201ccheck-ups\u201d and precau\ntions should, I think, be taken by\nthe banks themselves. Many banks\nhave also recently been discover\ning, after a crime has occurred,\nthat they are greatly under-in\nsured. In 45 recent bank embezzle\nments, I am informed that the\ntotal losses approximated over $4,-\n000,000 and the total insurance\n$728,000. During the last month\nalone, a savings bank of Grand\nRapids suffered an embezzlement\nreported to be $300,000 with only\n$50,000 insurance, and a bank in\nWilmington, Del., suffered an em\nbezzlement reported to be $200,-\n000 with only. $25,000 insurance.\nThe ease with which many re\ncent bank crimes have been com\nmitted is really startling. A young\nregistered mail clerk only a few\nweeks ago was able to rob liis\nbank of SII,OOO merely by stealing\nregistered letters containing cur\nrency. Young and untried bank\nemployes should not be allowed\nto handle letters which may con\ntain large amounts of currency,\nwithout very close supervision.\nA $1,400-a-year receiving- teller\nrecently succeeded in stealing\n$28,000 of the bank\u2019s money for\nsecret speculation merely by tak\ning cash from his drawer, charg\ning it against big- depositors, and\naltering their montlily statements\nbefore these were sent out. A\n$l5O-a-month southern bank\ncashier, who bad entire charge of\na small country bank, advertised\nto the whole country-side that he\nwas operating far beyond his saj\nary by building an elaborate home\nand a several-mile private road\nbetween it and the bank, lie con\ncealed thefts of depositors\u2019 money\nby closing out several large ac\ncounts on the current ledger and\ntaking an equal amount of cash\nfrom the vault. Ho kept a mem\norandum of tile real condition of\nthe \u201cclosed\u201d accounts in an old\nledger and took care to handle all\ndetails concerning them. In the\ncashier\u2019s absence, a large deposi\ntor was shocked to learn from a\nclerk that his account had been\n\u201cclosed.\u201d Discovery followed. A\nPennsylvania bank cashier has\nbeen similarly enabled to steal\n$22,000 for speculation through\nlack of supervision wind proper\noutside audits <md \u201ccheck-ups.\u201d\nIn this case, the loss fell chiefly on\nthe directors, as the fidelity insur\nance was only $5,000.\n\nA youth who embezzeled $1,295\nfrom a packing house in 1915, was\nable to get a position as ledger\nclerk in a Providence bank re\ncently through lack of sufficiently\ncareful investigation of his previ\nous record. He stole $1,600. We\npaid both losses.\nThe 23-year-ohl receiving teller\nin a New York bank recently em\nbezzled $3,400 in four months by\nsecretly destroying entry slips\nwhich his assistant in the cage was\nresponsible for and by taking an\nequal amount of cash from the\ndrawer. He tried to pin the guilt\non the assistant and only an in\nvestigation of the different night\nlives of both young men saved the\ninnocent one from going to Sing\nSing. This embezzler is typical of\nscores of young men who have\ngone from extravagance and dis\nsipation to desperation and crime\nsince the war.\nOne of the most pathetic and\nilluminating embezzlement re\nports which I have received re\ncently, on the other hand, concerns\na large New York state bank in\nwhich five different employes were\nrecently found short about S2OO\neach. None of these young men\nwere extravagant, dissipated or\ncriminal. But the cost of rent\nfood, clothes, fuel, furniture and\nother natural requirements had\nsimply risen above their salaries.\nft\nBank holdups and burglaries,\nthough much fewer in number and\nsmaller in total amount than em\nbezzlements, are constantly on tla;\nIncrease. They rose to 174 in 1919\nafter having averaged only 100 an\nnually for several years before.\nThe robberies, in many cases,\nhave not been committed by pro\nfessional outlaws. Many have been\nthe work of local unemployed or\nne\u2019er-do-wells, who have chanced\nto observe a flaw in some particu\nlar bank\u2019s defense system.\nA 19-year-old youth of Portland,\nOre., who came of good family, but\nwho formed bad friendships after\nIlls parents\u2019 death, recently\nlearned that a small bank in a dis-\nEDITORIAL PAGE\nPRICE THREE CENTS.\ntant hamlet was left in sole charge\nof a woman bookkeeper during\nthe noon lunch hour. Hiring an\nautomoo.lc and whirling into the\ndozmg dllago, he thrust a revolver\nin the girl's lace while she was\ncounting cash at the paying till\ner's wicket, made her push $4,000\nin currency and omuls Into hi\nopen satchel, thrust her and an\naged male depositor into the bank\nvault and disappeared, llut for a\ngrudge which Ins lather-in-law\nhad against him. his tracing to a\nLos Angeles hotel and the reinv\nery of $2,500 oi his booty inigh*\nnot have been accomplished.\n\nA worthless, but not profession\nally criminal, garage man in a\nsmall Texas town discovered that\nhis cousin, the cashier of the local\nbank, was alone with two women\nbookkeepers part of every day.\nWith lour other masked armed\nmen, he rushed into the bank,\ntbrust liis relative, the two women\nand two depositors into the vault,\nand whirled away with $0,500 in\ncash and securities. Unable to un\nlock the vault, the imprisoned\nhank folk wore nearly suffocated\nbefore associates returned, heard\ntheir cries and broke through the\nbrick work beside the fouhd steel\ndoor. Suspected because of his\ndisappearance, the garage man\nwas traced to Galveston and ar\nrested with $5,800 of the stolen\nmoney.\nIn Kansas and Oklahoma es\npecially, surety official-, govern\nment agents and local police, dur\ning the last three years, have been\nwaging continuous war against\nnumber of bank bandit gangs. In\n1917 and 1918 alone, more than\n25 daylight holdups of banks oc\ncurred in these two states. One\ngang had been organized by C.\nI. Fitzgerald. When Fitzgerald\nwas given seven years in El-worth\npenitentiary for holding up the\nExchange State bank of Kanapolis,\nliis followers, instead of becom\ning intimidated, increased their\ndepredations in order to get funds\nto obtain his release. The gang\nheld up a Kansas City gambling\nhouse and three policemen and\ntwo yeggmen fought a desperate\nrevolver battle in a dark alley.\nBoth bandits were wounded and\ncaptured, and trunks containing\n$20,000 in Liberty lmnds were\nfound in their hotel room. Later,\nthe Kansas City police ambushed\na motor car used by the bandits\nand found in it SBI,OOO in cash ami\nbonds. Four members of another\nKansas gang recently whirled into\na hamlet near Wichita, rushed the\nsmall bank, locked the man\ncashier, girl bookkeeper and two\ndepositors in the vault and took\n$20,000 in Liberty bonds and\n$2,000.\nBank daylight holdups take\nplace In eastern states also. While\nthe girl cashier of a small Penn\nsylvania hank was trying to locate\na shortage of 22 cents shortly after\nthe opening hour, three masked\nbandits thrust revolvers in her\nface and made her push over $50,-\n000 in Liberty bonds. Tlic man\ncashier jumped for his gun, but\nbefore he could reach his desk he\nwas covered and locked in the\nvault with a male depositor. Xc\ntrace has yet been found of the\nrobbers.\nPreferring to operate at night,\nother bank bandit gangs have\nshown that many small town\nbanks can be successfully burg\nlarized with little trouble or risk\nRobbers recently pinch-barred\nthe flimsy rear door of a small\nNorth Carolina college town bank,\nhammered off the combination of\nthe safe, nitroglycerined the door,\ndeadening the explosion with the\noffice carpet, and disappeared with\n$14,000 in cash anil bonds. A\nsmall Illinois bank, not long ago,\nlost $4,500 through similar meth\nods.\u2014The Financier, New York,\nThree Monkeys\nBY ANISE.\nStaff Writer for The Federated I\u2019reM.\nThree monkeys, it is said,\nOnce on a time\nSat in a tree\nDiscussing weighty things.\n\u2018What do you think,\u201d said one,\n\u201cAbout this rumor\nThat MEN\nAre our descendants?\nl>o you believe that THEY\u2019\nCould ever come\nFroia US?\u201d\n\u201cNo,\u201d said the first.\n\u201cI hardly think it likely;\nWho ever heard of mor keys\nThat*'would take poisonous weed\u00ae\nAnd mince them up\nIn a wooden bowl\nWith a long pipe,\nAnd, setting fire to it.\nCreate a nauseous smoke\nAnd call it PLEASURE!\u201d\n\u201cAnd surely,\u201d said the second,\n\u201cNo monkey EVER\nConcocted poisonous DRINKS\nThat made him tumble\nFrom side to side.\nFor every monkey knows\nHe needs his WITS!\nThese MEN\nWho place no value upon brains\u2014\nBnt muddle them for fun\u2014\nAre not from VS!\u201d\n\u201cNay,\u201d said the tfrirtf,\n\u201cA creature is not judged\nBy what he calls\nHis pleasures;\nThese are idle fruit\nOf idle moments.\nAnd change with custom.\nBut see the way\nTHAT CREATURE makes\nHis LIVING!\nWhat monkeys ever\nWould let one monkey\nMake a FENCE\nAround the eoeoanut tree\nAnd keep the rest away?\nCreatures that starve\nIn WILLINGNESS\nWhile others waste;\nWE would disown them;\nThey are cot from us:*\u2019\u2019","height":"28107","width":"21882"}}
